to rearrange the field trip for Friday?

247
00:23:18,774 --> 00:23:20,984
All right? I'll be back
as soon as I can.

248
00:23:21,068 --> 00:23:24,655
He probably just wants me to retie his bandages.
Okay, I'll see you later.

249
00:23:33,872 --> 00:23:36,333
My name is Masanga.

250
00:23:36,458 --> 00:23:38,961
Nice to meet you.
I'm Nicholas.

251
00:23:39,044 --> 00:23:41,797
Pleased to meet you,
Mr. Nicholas.

252
00:23:41,880 --> 00:23:44,341
Welcome
to the president's car.

253
00:23:49,721 --> 00:23:52,182
<i>- They think you are the president.
- Eh?</i>

254
00:23:52,266 --> 00:23:56,353
They think you are the president.

255
00:24:57,664 --> 00:24:59,625
The president's house.

256
00:25:04,796 --> 00:25:07,090
Please sit down.

257
00:25:07,174 --> 00:25:09,259
His Excellency
will be with you in a moment.

258
00:25:09,343 --> 00:25:13,931
- And who's this?
- Oh. Dr. Junju, the previous incumbent.

259
00:25:14,056 --> 00:25:17,267
<i>- Of what?
- Of the post...</i>

260
00:25:17,351 --> 00:25:19,937
of personal physician to the president.

261
00:25:20,979 --> 00:25:22,773
Hold on to your guns!

262
00:25:22,856 --> 00:25:25,067
Everyone!
Hold on to your guns!

263
00:25:28,195 --> 00:25:30,781
- Good to see you again, Dr. Garrigan.
- You too.

264
00:25:30,864 --> 00:25:35,118
You see, Jonah? This is the sort of man
a president needs around him-

265
00:25:35,244 --> 00:25:37,871
someone who is not afraid
to speak his mind.

266
00:25:39,665 --> 00:25:41,875
So, what do you say,
Nicholas?

267
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:44,753
Will you take the job?

268
00:25:44,837 --> 00:25:46,755
Wha- I'm sorry.
Um-

269
00:25:46,839 --> 00:25:50,342
- You want me to be your physician?
- Mmm.

270
00:25:50,467 --> 00:25:55,347
- Do you want to be of service to Uganda, Dr. Garrigan?
- Yes, I do.

271
00:25:55,430 --> 00:25:57,516
Then what better way...

272
00:25:57,641 --> 00:26:00,519
than to look after the health
of its president?

273
00:26:00,602 --> 00:26:04,147
And let me tell you,
it will not be a difficult job.

274
00:26:04,273 --> 00:26:07,401
Because me, myself,
I am a man...

275
00:26:07,526 --> 00:26:10,404
in perfect physical condition.

276
00:26:10,529 --> 00:26:15,033
Also, I know precisely
when I will die.

277
00:26:15,158 --> 00:26:18,287
It came to me in a dream.

278
00:26:18,370 --> 00:26:20,956
So, you do not have to worry
about making a mistake.

279
00:26:23,625 --> 00:26:27,546
- I'm really sorry. I'm-I'm very honored, but-
- Nicholas.

280
00:26:27,629 --> 00:26:30,048
I understand.

281
00:26:30,132 --> 00:26:33,260
Me, myself, I did not
want to be president.

282
00:26:33,385 --> 00:26:35,345
But the people,
they wanted it so.

283
00:26:36,805 --> 00:26:40,934
Listen to me.
This is very important.

284
00:26:41,059 --> 00:26:43,437
Here, in Kampala...

285
00:26:43,562 --> 00:26:45,522
you will have a hand
in creating...

286
00:26:45,606 --> 00:26:48,358
a new health service
for this country-

287
00:26:48,442 --> 00:26:51,778
something that will help
millions of people.

288
00:26:54,072 --> 00:26:57,993
I'm sorry. I really do have a commitment
to the mission in Mgambo.

289
00:26:58,076 --> 00:27:00,662
I'd be lettin' them down
horribly. You see?

290
00:27:08,086 --> 00:27:10,631
Ah.

291
00:27:10,756 --> 00:27:13,509
It's the woman,
the one I saw you with.

292
00:27:13,592 --> 00:27:15,594
You want to get back
to be with her.

293
00:27:15,677 --> 00:27:18,597
Well, not entirely.

294
00:27:18,680 --> 00:27:21,600
It's the woman.
It's the woman.

295
00:27:21,683 --> 00:27:24,895
Why don't you tell her
to come and be here with us?

296
00:27:24,978 --> 00:27:27,397
Uh, well, it's not
that simple.

297
00:27:27,481 --> 00:27:29,566
- It's quite complicated actually.
- Why?

298
00:27:31,026 --> 00:27:34,321
- Is she married?
- Yes, she is.

299
00:27:36,782 --> 00:27:39,660
Ah, Doctor.

300
00:27:39,785 --> 00:27:42,829
Doctor, you-
you are very naughty.

301
00:27:42,955 --> 00:27:46,166
Me?

302
00:27:46,291 --> 00:27:49,378
Ah, now you are
even more interesting.

303
00:27:49,461 --> 00:27:54,383
Married women, they are always
the most passionate, huh?

304
00:27:54,466 --> 00:27:56,468
Yes.

305
00:27:56,552 --> 00:27:58,512
- It's true.
- They are so grateful, huh?

306
00:28:03,308 --> 00:28:05,227
Hmm. Yes.

307
00:28:06,979 --> 00:28:09,606
I'm sorry. Yes, I'm sorry
for wasting your time.

308
00:28:09,690 --> 00:28:11,608
No, no.

309
00:28:11,692 --> 00:28:15,279
My car will take you back
first thing in the morning.

310
00:28:15,362 --> 00:28:20,742
But, in the meantime-
Tonight, we are having a state dinner.

311
00:28:20,826 --> 00:28:22,870
Please, would you
join us there?

312
00:28:22,995 --> 00:28:24,955
I'd very much like that.
Thank you.

313
00:28:25,038 --> 00:28:28,208
You have a suit?
Dark suit?

314
00:28:28,333 --> 00:28:30,919
- No. No, I don't.
- Hmm.

315
00:28:43,682 --> 00:28:46,101
How much is this gonna
cost me, by the way?

316
00:28:46,185 --> 00:28:48,103
It's okay.
It's the president's account.

317
00:28:50,856 --> 00:28:54,151
<i>- Oh, can I just-
- Hey! Stop!</i>

318
00:29:03,285 --> 00:29:05,662
<i>- What's goin' on?
- Obote's men.</i>

319
00:29:05,746 --> 00:29:09,082
- They're everywhere.
- Really?

320
00:29:09,208 --> 00:29:12,669
Yep. They're communists,
you know?

321
00:29:12,794 --> 00:29:15,797
Mind you, Amin's
more than a match for them.

322
00:29:15,881 --> 00:29:18,675
He's ex-British army-
King's African Rifles.

323
00:29:18,800 --> 00:29:20,719
- Uh, Jamshid.
- Yes, sir?

324
00:29:20,802 --> 00:29:24,306
Pack those up and have them sent to the
High Commission in the morning, please. Thanks.

325
00:29:24,389 --> 00:29:26,391
<i>Yes, he's a little
unpredictable...</i>

326
00:29:26,475 --> 00:29:29,394
but he's got
a firm hand.

327
00:29:29,520 --> 00:29:31,939
Only thing the African really understands.

328
00:29:32,064 --> 00:29:34,900
<i>- Thanks, Jamshid.
- You're welcome.</i>

329
00:29:39,071 --> 00:29:43,033
Yeah, up yours too, pal.
Bloody English.

330
00:30:05,848 --> 00:30:08,892
Hello.

331
00:30:13,272 --> 00:30:15,190
Hello.

332
00:30:19,111 --> 00:30:22,114
Hello there.
How do you do?

333
00:30:22,197 --> 00:30:24,616
- Ah! Nicholas.
- Oh!

334
00:30:24,741 --> 00:30:26,702
- I'm so happy you came.
- So am I.

335
00:30:26,785 --> 00:30:30,205
Please. Please, this way.
I want to introduce you to my wives.

336
00:30:30,289 --> 00:30:33,083
Excuse me. Here.
This is Malyamu.

337
00:30:33,166 --> 00:30:35,419
She is my first wife.
She has given me five children.

338
00:30:35,502 --> 00:30:37,713
Hello.

339
00:30:37,796 --> 00:30:40,674
<i>And this one- Nora.
She has given me three.</i>

340
00:30:40,799 --> 00:30:42,801
Hello.

341
00:30:42,926 --> 00:30:46,013
And that here
is Kay. Yes.

342
00:30:46,138 --> 00:30:48,765
<i>- This is Dr. Nicholas Garrigan.
- Hello.</i>

343
00:30:48,849 --> 00:30:51,935
- He saved my life.
- Oh, wel- Really, I just stitched his hand up.

344
00:30:52,060 --> 00:30:54,271
<i>- It was-
- Don't be so modest.</i>

345
00:30:54,354 --> 00:30:56,940
I believe it is you
I have to thank for the T-shirt.

346
00:30:57,024 --> 00:31:00,235
Oh, right.
So you must be Campbell's mother.

347
00:31:00,319 --> 00:31:03,238
- Yes.
- It's a pleasure meeting you.

348
00:31:03,322 --> 00:31:06,074
Please come. I have to introduce you
to some people here.

349
00:31:08,493 --> 00:31:10,412
Excuse me.

350
00:31:10,495 --> 00:31:14,791
- This is, uh, British High Commissioner, Mr. Perkins.
- How do you do?

351
00:31:14,917 --> 00:31:18,253
Please, meet my good friend
Dr. Nicholas Garrigan.

352
00:31:18,337 --> 00:31:20,214
<i>And his colleague
Mr. Stone.</i>

353
00:31:20,339 --> 00:31:23,050
- How do you do?
- Fine. Yes, we've already met.

354
00:31:23,175 --> 00:31:26,136
- Well, I will talk with you later.
- Oh, right.

355
00:31:26,261 --> 00:31:30,432
So, uh, Dr. Garrigan, we've been hearing
all sorts of things about you.

356
00:31:30,516 --> 00:31:34,144
Yes, I, uh- I gather the president
has clasped you to his bosom.

357
00:31:34,228 --> 00:31:36,522
Uh, no, no.
Not exactly.

358
00:31:36,647 --> 00:31:38,649
What do you
make of him?

359
00:31:38,732 --> 00:31:40,651
Well, I think he's doing
rather a great job.

360
00:31:40,734 --> 00:31:44,071
- Don't you?
- Yes. He has some issues to be sorted out.

361
00:31:44,196 --> 00:31:46,281
But, no, he plays
a pretty straight bat.

362
00:31:46,365 --> 00:31:49,284
- Yes, definitely one of us.
- Anyway...

363
00:31:49,368 --> 00:31:52,204
it's very good to, uh,
have another Englishman around.

364
00:31:52,329 --> 00:31:53,997
- Scot.
- What?

365
00:31:54,122 --> 00:31:58,168
I'm a Scotsman.

366
00:32:00,420 --> 00:32:03,674
Ladies and gentlemen,
friends.

367
00:32:03,757 --> 00:32:07,302
<i>I am speaking with you now
because if I wait until later...</i>

368
00:32:07,386 --> 00:32:09,847
you will be too drunk
to hear my voice.

369
00:32:12,724 --> 00:32:17,020
<i>- Here is where civilization began.
- Yes.</i>

370
00:32:17,104 --> 00:32:19,106
Here in Africa.

371
00:32:19,231 --> 00:32:24,069
<i>Here is where the Greeks
stole their philosophy...</i>

372
00:32:24,194 --> 00:32:27,573
and the Arabs took
their medicine.

373
00:32:27,656 --> 00:32:32,327
We Ugandans must be more proud
of this history.

374
00:32:32,411 --> 00:32:36,331
<i>We are an independent
African nation...</i>

375
00:32:36,415 --> 00:32:40,544
<i>living in peace
and economic power.</i>

376
00:32:42,004 --> 00:32:45,340
- Black power.
- Yes.

377
00:32:45,424 --> 00:32:49,261
Just like all you people
thought would never be possible.

378
00:32:52,764 --> 00:32:54,725
<i>And now we will go through
to dinner.</i>

379
00:32:54,808 --> 00:32:58,395
The food tonight,
it is all local...

380
00:32:58,520 --> 00:33:00,939
special food.

381
00:33:01,023 --> 00:33:03,358
And none of it
is human flesh.

382
00:33:05,527 --> 00:33:07,988
This is my last.

383
00:33:18,665 --> 00:33:22,252
Dr. Garrigan. Please come quickly.
The president is very sick.

384
00:33:22,377 --> 00:33:25,339
They have poisoned me.

385
00:33:25,464 --> 00:33:28,175
They are trying
to assassinate me.

386
00:33:28,300 --> 00:33:31,094
- Nicholas.
- Okay.

387
00:33:31,178 --> 00:33:33,639
I just have to examine
your stomach.

388
00:33:35,724 --> 00:33:39,019
<i>Obote's people are everywhere.
They want me dead, Nicholas.</i>

389
00:33:39,144 --> 00:33:42,439
Okay, I'm just-
I need to do this. Okay?

390
00:33:42,523 --> 00:33:44,983
One more. One more.

391
00:33:45,067 --> 00:33:47,402
Okay. Okay.

392
00:33:47,486 --> 00:33:50,113
Okay.

393
00:33:52,866 --> 00:33:56,453
Okay. I think I know what this is.
Let me listen, just listen.

394
00:34:01,542 --> 00:34:04,086
Okay. Yeah, okay.
I think I know what this is.

395
00:34:04,169 --> 00:34:08,674
Bear with me. Uh-

396
00:34:11,134 --> 00:34:13,095
There we go.

397
00:34:16,849 --> 00:34:19,226
There we are.
Okay.

398
00:34:19,351 --> 00:34:21,728
I'm gonna ask you
to sit on this pouf right here.

399
00:34:27,234 --> 00:34:29,486
- Hey! What is this?
- It's okay. It's okay.

400
00:34:29,611 --> 00:34:32,155
- What is this?
- It's okay. I'm just gonna hold it against your stomach.

401
00:34:32,281 --> 00:34:34,491
<i>I'm gonna ask you to stand up...
in three.</i>

402
00:34:34,575 --> 00:34:38,161
One, two, three. Go.

403
00:34:58,390 --> 00:35:01,518
I feel better,
much better.

404
00:35:01,643 --> 00:35:05,689
<i>Ah. Ah, yes.</i>

405
00:35:05,814 --> 00:35:08,859
You are a good doctor.
Thank you.

406
00:35:08,984 --> 00:35:12,696
In future, remember
not to mix beer with aspirin.

407
00:35:15,240 --> 00:35:19,036
- That was the cause?
- I think so, yes.

408
00:35:19,119 --> 00:35:23,207
I am ashamed
that you saw me like that.

409
00:35:23,290 --> 00:35:27,503
- I was frightened.
- I'm a doctor.

410
00:35:27,586 --> 00:35:30,380
Everything that passes between us
is confidential.

411
00:35:30,506 --> 00:35:33,050
Okay? I've taken an oath.

412
00:35:33,175 --> 00:35:38,347
But a man who shows fear,
he is weak...

413
00:35:38,430 --> 00:35:41,183
and he is a slave.

414
00:35:41,266 --> 00:35:44,144
Well, if you're afraid
of dying...

415
00:35:44,269 --> 00:35:46,230
it shows you have
a life worth keeping.

416
00:35:48,440 --> 00:35:50,359
Ah.

417
00:35:52,027 --> 00:35:53,946
You see?

418
00:35:54,029 --> 00:35:58,075
You are a doctor...
and also a philosopher.

419
00:35:58,200 --> 00:36:01,161
Yes.

420
00:36:01,286 --> 00:36:04,248
I do have
a good life now.

421
00:36:04,373 --> 00:36:06,792
Please.
Please, sit.

422
00:36:06,875 --> 00:36:08,794
Sit here.
Sit here.

423
00:36:13,382 --> 00:36:17,094
I come from...
a very poor family.

424
00:36:17,177 --> 00:36:19,221
I think
you should know this.

425
00:36:19,304 --> 00:36:21,390
My father, he left me
when I was a child.

426
00:36:21,473 --> 00:36:24,852
The British army,
it became my home.

427
00:36:24,977 --> 00:36:28,814
They took me as a...

428
00:36:28,897 --> 00:36:33,193
cleaner in the kitchen,
cleaning pots.

429
00:36:33,318 --> 00:36:35,279
They used to beat me.

430
00:36:37,698 --> 00:36:40,242
"Build this wall, Amin. "

431
00:36:40,325 --> 00:36:42,953
"Dig this latrine, Amin. "

432
00:36:43,036 --> 00:36:47,249
And now here I am,
the president of Uganda.

433
00:36:49,168 --> 00:36:51,086
And who put me here?
Huh?

434
00:36:53,964 --> 00:36:57,217
It was the British.

435
00:36:59,094 --> 00:37:01,430
What a story.

436
00:37:03,682 --> 00:37:06,768
- Good night, Nicholas.
- Good night, sir.

437
00:37:23,035 --> 00:37:24,995
<i>Uh, hello. Sarah, it's Nicholas.</i>

438
00:37:25,120 --> 00:37:28,332
<i>- Nicholas, where are you?
- I'm still in Kampala actually.</i>

439
00:37:28,415 --> 00:37:30,125
Thank you.

440
00:37:30,209 --> 00:37:33,337
<i>Look, the president's
offered me a job here.</i>

441
00:37:33,462 --> 00:37:35,422
<i>Normally, I wouldn't even
bother considering it.</i>

442
00:37:35,547 --> 00:37:39,801
<i>- But, under the circumstances...
- Thank you.</i>

443
00:37:39,885 --> 00:37:42,596
<i>I thought it might
be quite a good idea.</i>

444
00:37:44,723 --> 00:37:46,975
<i>Oh, I see.</i>

445
00:37:47,059 --> 00:37:49,311
David will be disappointed.

446
00:37:49,394 --> 00:37:52,814
Oh, well, I'll write to David.
Of course I will.

447
00:37:52,898 --> 00:37:54,816
Of course.

448
00:37:54,900 --> 00:37:58,028
I just hope you can do as much good there
as you could've done here.

449
00:37:58,153 --> 00:38:00,489
Look, somebody's
callin' me.

450
00:38:00,572 --> 00:38:03,784
I'd, uh, better go.

451
00:38:03,909 --> 00:38:07,371
- Sure.
- All right. Well, listen. Bye, Sarah.

452
00:38:07,496 --> 00:38:10,707
- I'll be in touch.
- Bye.

453
00:38:26,348 --> 00:38:30,269
<i>When you're not treating
the president or his family...</i>

454
00:38:30,352 --> 00:38:33,564
the hospital could use
your expertise here.

455
00:38:37,776 --> 00:38:41,655
<i>This is one
of our new medical wards.</i>

456
00:38:44,616 --> 00:38:47,911
Farther down the corridor
will be the operating theaters...

457
00:38:48,036 --> 00:38:49,955
which the president
has paid for himself.

458
00:38:50,080 --> 00:38:52,749
<i>- Yes, sir.
- Hi, Doctor.</i>

459
00:38:52,875 --> 00:38:56,587
- Welcome to Mulago, Dr. -
- Garrigan. Hello.

460
00:38:56,670 --> 00:39:00,966
I do hope you find the hospital
up to the standard you are used to.

461
00:39:04,928 --> 00:39:07,931
Uh, excuse me.
Who was that?

462
00:39:08,056 --> 00:39:11,393
Your predecessor-
Dr. Junju.

463
00:39:11,476 --> 00:39:15,105
<i>- Never mind him.
- Excuse me, sir. Two men to see you.</i>

464
00:39:15,230 --> 00:39:18,275
- Excuse me a moment.
- Of course.

465
00:39:21,778 --> 00:39:24,948
- Hello. Jolly nice of you.
- It's very nice.

466
00:39:31,997 --> 00:39:35,083
<i>Dr. Garrigan.</i>

467
00:39:35,167 --> 00:39:38,170
Just topping up on quinine.

468
00:39:38,253 --> 00:39:40,172
So, you've decided to stay.

469
00:39:40,255 --> 00:39:42,382
- Uh, yes. Yes, I did.
- Excellent. Excellent.

470
00:39:42,508 --> 00:39:44,468
Well, listen,
I just wanted to say...

471
00:39:44,551 --> 00:39:47,513
that if there's anything
we can possibly help you with...

472
00:39:47,596 --> 00:39:49,640
please don't, um,
hesitate.

473
00:39:49,765 --> 00:39:52,434
What, you're my new best friend now?

474
00:39:54,520 --> 00:39:58,065
Do just stay in touch.

475
00:39:58,190 --> 00:40:00,400
Why?

476
00:40:00,526 --> 00:40:02,819
Well, given
that we were so, uh...

477
00:40:04,863 --> 00:40:09,243
<i>intimately involved
with the president coming to... power...</i>

478
00:40:09,368 --> 00:40:13,288
the Foreign Office has asked me
to point out our awareness...

479
00:40:13,372 --> 00:40:17,835
of your very unique personal relationship
with President Amin.

480
00:40:17,960 --> 00:40:19,878
Mm-hmm?

481
00:40:19,962 --> 00:40:24,508
Should you find the need to clarify your status...

482
00:40:24,591 --> 00:40:27,261
regarding the details
of that relationship...

483
00:40:27,386 --> 00:40:29,513
we would of course welcome
any clarification you might...

484
00:40:29,638 --> 00:40:33,308
feel the need to share with us.

485
00:40:36,895 --> 00:40:39,690
Is there some special school
where you people...

486
00:40:39,773 --> 00:40:42,109
learn to talk
that bollocks?

487
00:40:45,112 --> 00:40:49,199
Do, please, stay in touch.

488
00:40:49,324 --> 00:40:51,451
You-You take care now.

489
00:40:59,668 --> 00:41:02,254
This man is going to kill-
He's going to kill the president.

490
00:41:02,379 --> 00:41:05,215
So Nicholas walks up to that cow,
and he shoots it in the head.

491
00:41:07,968 --> 00:41:09,887
On your marks!

492
00:41:09,970 --> 00:41:12,598
Get set!

493
00:41:12,723 --> 00:41:14,766
Go!

494
00:41:14,892 --> 00:41:18,228
Amin! Amin!

495
00:41:21,982 --> 00:41:24,568
- Ho!
- I won.

496
00:41:33,702 --> 00:41:37,414
Hit my hand. Yes.

497
00:41:37,497 --> 00:41:40,459
- Okay. Nicholas.
- Oh, no, no, no.

498
00:41:45,506 --> 00:41:48,967
Before I forget,
I need to ask a favor.

499
00:41:49,051 --> 00:41:50,969
Anything.

500
00:41:51,053 --> 00:41:53,013
I will be in Libya
next week...

501
00:41:53,138 --> 00:41:55,349
and I need you to attend
a meeting in my place.

502
00:41:55,474 --> 00:42:00,562
- What kind of meeting?
- A simple matter of taste and common sense.

503
00:42:02,189 --> 00:42:04,816
I cannot think of anyone
better than you.

504
00:42:17,663 --> 00:42:20,707
Ah, gentlemen, please.
Don't get up.

505
00:42:20,832 --> 00:42:22,876
<i>The president
sends his apologies.</i>

506
00:42:23,001 --> 00:42:25,963
He's been called away-
on short notice.

507
00:42:26,046 --> 00:42:28,590
He's asked me to step in.

508
00:42:28,674 --> 00:42:32,553
- And you are?
- Nicholas Garrigan, his doctor.

509
00:42:33,762 --> 00:42:36,473
<i>- His doctor?
- Yes.</i>

510
00:42:36,557 --> 00:42:41,103
- And you are?
